    <item>
      <title>PWM SAM7x</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_sam7x/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 27 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_sam7x/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_SAMx7.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_SAMx7.png&#34; alt=&#34;Pwm Sam7X Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        Advanced PWM peripheral for SAM ARM Cortex-M microcontrollers. Provides complementary PWM with dead-time, fault protection, and pattern generation for motor control applications.&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;overview&#34;&gt;Overview&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The PWM SAM7x block configures the Pulse Width Modulation Controller (PWMC) peripheral on SAME7x/SAMS7x/SAMV7x microcontrollers. Each controller (PWM0 or PWM1) supports up to 4 independent PWM channels with complementary high/low outputs, programmable dead-time, and fault protection.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Motor control and power conversion on SAM E7x, SAM S7x, SAM V7x, or SAM RH71 devices&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Applications requiring up to 4 complementary PWM channels per controller (8 total with PWM0+PWM1)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Push-pull mode for half-bridge topologies&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;PWM event line triggers for ADC synchronization (8 comparators)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When NOT to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>MCPWM</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/mcpwm/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/mcpwm/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_MCPWM.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_MCPWM.png&#34; alt=&#34;Mcpwm Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        MCPWM (Motor Control PWM) offers enhanced features beyond standard PWM blocks, including programmable fault sources with digital comparator inputs, leading-edge blanking, dead-time compensation modes, and extensive trigger output capabilities for ADC synchronization.&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Advanced motor control on PIC32MK or dsPIC33A/dsPIC33C (devices with MCPWM peripheral)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Applications requiring comparator-based fault inputs and leading-edge blanking&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Dead-time compensation with current direction sensing&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Multiple trigger outputs (TRIG1/2/3 + SEVTCMP) for complex ADC synchronization&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When NOT to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>PWM</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM.png&#34; alt=&#34;Pwm Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        The PWM block supports up to 4 complementary PWM channel pairs with independent duty cycle control, dead-time insertion, fault protection, and special event triggers for ADC synchronization.&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Motor control and power conversion on dsPIC30F, dsPIC33F, or dsPIC33E (EP/EV/FJ) devices&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Applications requiring up to 4 complementary PWM pairs with dead-time and fault protection&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;PWM-synchronized ADC triggering for current/voltage sensing&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Legacy projects targeting older dsPIC families&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When NOT to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>PWM HighSpeed</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_highspeed/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_highspeed/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_HS.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_HS.png&#34; alt=&#34;Pwm Highspeed Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        This block is designed for demanding motor control and power conversion applications requiring precise timing, independent channel control, and high switching frequencies.&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;High-speed motor control on dsPIC33C/CH/CK or dsPIC33E (GS) devices&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Applications requiring independent time bases per PWM channel&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Multiple ADC trigger outputs per PWM cycle (advanced control)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Double update mode for asymmetric center-aligned PWM&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When NOT to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;dsPIC33A devices → use &lt;a href=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_hs_fep/&#34;&gt;PWM HS FEP&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; for fine edge placement (16× resolution)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;dsPIC30F or standard dsPIC33F/33E → use &lt;a href=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm/&#34;&gt;PWM&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; for standard PWM peripheral&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;SAM devices → use &lt;a href=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/tcc_pwm/&#34;&gt;TCC PWM&lt;/a&gt;&#xA; or &lt;a href=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_sam7x/&#34;&gt;PWM SAM7x&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;block-dialog&#34;&gt;Block Dialog&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;block-screenshots-fallback&#34; style=&#34;margin:15px 0;&#34;&gt;&lt;figure style=&#34;margin:15px auto; max-width:700px;&#34;&gt;&#xA;          &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/gui/pwm_hs_output_override_tab1_main.png&#34; alt=&#34;pwm_hs_output_override — Tab 1: Main&#34;&#xA;               style=&#34;width:100%; display:block; border:1px solid #ddd; border-radius:4px;&#34;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;p style=&#34;text-align:center; font-size:0.9em; color:#666; margin-top:10px;&#34;&gt;&#xA;          &lt;em&gt;Screenshots taken with chip &lt;code&gt;33EP64MC506&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&#xA;        &lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>PWM HighSpeed Override</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_highspeed_override/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_highspeed_override/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_HS_Override.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_HS_Override.png&#34; alt=&#34;Pwm Highspeed Override Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        The override block works in conjunction with the &lt;strong&gt;MCHP_PWM_HighSpeed&lt;/strong&gt; block and can force PWM outputs to specific logic levels regardless of the PWM generator state. &lt;strong&gt;Important:&lt;/strong&gt; Override control should be used with extreme caution in motor control applications, as improper use can cause hardware damage or create hazardous conditions.  ## Supported Device Families  This block supports the same device families as MCHP_PWM_HighSpeed:  - &lt;strong&gt;dsPIC33F (selected)&lt;/strong&gt; - with high-speed PWM module - &lt;strong&gt;dsPIC33EP (GS)&lt;/strong&gt; - with auxiliary clock support - &lt;strong&gt;dsPIC33C/CH/CK&lt;/strong&gt; - full-featured implementations&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>PWM HS FEP</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_hs_fep/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_hs_fep/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_HS_FEP.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_HS_FEP.png&#34; alt=&#34;Pwm Hs Fep Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        This advanced PWM peripheral is specifically designed for precision motor control, high-frequency power conversion, and applications demanding superior timing accuracy and reduced total harmonic distortion (THD).&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Precision motor control on dsPIC33A or dsPIC33C (selected devices with FEP module)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Applications requiring fine edge placement (16× enhanced resolution in HiRES mode)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;High-resolution PWM for reduced harmonic distortion&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;32-bit register width for extended range (dsPIC33A)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;When NOT to use:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>PWM SAM7x Override</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_sam7x_override/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 27 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/pwm_sam7x_override/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_SAMx7_Override.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_PWM_SAMx7_Override.png&#34; alt=&#34;Pwm Sam7X Override Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        Direct control of PWM output pins for SAM7x devices, allowing software override of PWM signals for safety shutdown, diagnostics, and custom patterns.&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;block-dialog&#34;&gt;Block Dialog&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;block-tabs&#34; data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34; role=&#34;region&#34; aria-label=&#34;Block dialog tabs&#34; style=&#34;margin:20px 0;&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;style&gt;&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] { border:1px solid #ddd; border-radius:6px; overflow:hidden; background:#fafafa; }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] input[type=&#34;radio&#34;] { display:none; }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] .bt-strip {&#xA;            display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:0; background:#eaeaea;&#xA;            border-bottom:1px solid #ccc; padding:0;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] .bt-strip label {&#xA;            padding:8px 14px; cursor:pointer; user-select:none;&#xA;            font-size:0.9em; color:#444; border-right:1px solid #ccc;&#xA;            transition:background 0.12s ease;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] .bt-strip label:hover { background:#dcdcdc; }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] .bt-panel {&#xA;            display:none; padding:14px; text-align:center; background:#fff;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] .bt-panel img {&#xA;            max-width:100%; height:auto; border:1px solid #ddd; border-radius:3px;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] .bt-caption {&#xA;            padding:8px 14px 12px; text-align:center; font-style:italic;&#xA;            color:#666; font-size:0.88em; border-top:1px solid #eee; background:#fafafa;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] .bt-caption code {&#xA;            background:#eef; padding:2px 6px; border-radius:3px; font-style:normal;&#xA;          }.block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r1:checked ~ .bt-strip label[for=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r1&#34;] {&#xA;            background:#fff; color:#0066cc; font-weight:600; border-bottom:2px solid #0066cc; margin-bottom:-1px;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r1:checked ~ .bt-panels #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-p1 {&#xA;            display:block;&#xA;          }.block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r2:checked ~ .bt-strip label[for=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r2&#34;] {&#xA;            background:#fff; color:#0066cc; font-weight:600; border-bottom:2px solid #0066cc; margin-bottom:-1px;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r2:checked ~ .bt-panels #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-p2 {&#xA;            display:block;&#xA;          }.block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r3:checked ~ .bt-strip label[for=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r3&#34;] {&#xA;            background:#fff; color:#0066cc; font-weight:600; border-bottom:2px solid #0066cc; margin-bottom:-1px;&#xA;          }&#xA;          .block-tabs[data-uid=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34;] #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r3:checked ~ .bt-panels #blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-p3 {&#xA;            display:block;&#xA;          }&lt;/style&gt;&lt;input type=&#34;radio&#34; name=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34; id=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r1&#34; checked&gt;&lt;input type=&#34;radio&#34; name=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34; id=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r2&#34;&gt;&lt;input type=&#34;radio&#34; name=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override&#34; id=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r3&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;bt-strip&#34;&gt;&lt;label for=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r1&#34;&gt;1. Main&lt;/label&gt;&lt;label for=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r2&#34;&gt;2. Initial Values&lt;/label&gt;&lt;label for=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-r3&#34;&gt;3. Block Inputs&lt;/label&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;        &lt;div class=&#34;bt-panels&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;bt-panel&#34; id=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-p1&#34;&gt;&#xA;              &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/gui/pwm_sam7x_output_override_tab1_main.png&#34; alt=&#34;pwm_sam7x_output_override — Tab 1: Main&#34;&gt;&#xA;            &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;bt-panel&#34; id=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-p2&#34;&gt;&#xA;              &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/gui/pwm_sam7x_output_override_tab2_initial_values.png&#34; alt=&#34;pwm_sam7x_output_override — Tab 2: Initial Values&#34;&gt;&#xA;            &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;bt-panel&#34; id=&#34;blocktabs-pwm-sam7x-output-override-p3&#34;&gt;&#xA;              &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/gui/pwm_sam7x_output_override_tab3_block_inputs.png&#34; alt=&#34;pwm_sam7x_output_override — Tab 3: Block Inputs&#34;&gt;&#xA;            &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;bt-caption&#34;&gt;&#xA;            Screenshots taken with chip &lt;code&gt;SAME70Q21B - UFBGA144&lt;/code&gt;&#xA;          &lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;overview&#34;&gt;Overview&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The PWM SAM7x Override block provides &lt;strong&gt;direct control&lt;/strong&gt; over PWM output pins by writing to the PWM Controller&amp;rsquo;s Output Override registers (PWM_OS, PWM_OSS, PWM_OSC, PWM_OOV). This allows forcing specific logic states on PWMH/PWML pins &lt;strong&gt;independently of the PWM waveform generator&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>TCC PWM</title>
      <link>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/tcc_pwm/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 27 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/block/pwm_io/tcc_pwm/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-image&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;picture&gt;&#xA;        &lt;source srcset=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_TCC_PWM.svg&#34; type=&#34;image/svg+xml&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img src=&#34;https://mplab-blockset.github.io/MPLAB-Device-Blocks-for-Simulink/images/blocks/block_TCC_PWM.png&#34; alt=&#34;Tcc Pwm Block Icon&#34;&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/picture&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;block-icon-description&#34;&gt;&#xA;        Timer/Counter for Control (TCC) PWM peripheral for SAM microcontrollers. Features advanced pattern generation, complementary outputs with dead-time, and fault protection for motor control.&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;overview&#34;&gt;Overview&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The TCC PWM block configures the &lt;strong&gt;Timer/Counter for Control (TCC)&lt;/strong&gt; peripheral on SAME5x, SAMC2x, and SAMD2x microcontrollers. TCC modules provide advanced PWM generation with:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Complementary output pairs&lt;/strong&gt; (WO0+WO4, WO1+WO5, etc.) with programmable dead-time&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Output matrix&lt;/strong&gt; (OTMX) to map compare channels (CCx) to waveform outputs (WOx)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pattern generator&lt;/strong&gt; for BLDC motor commutation (hardware-assisted 6-step)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Recoverable and non-recoverable faults&lt;/strong&gt; with configurable output states&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dual-slope (center-aligned)&lt;/strong&gt; and single-slope (left-aligned) counting&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dithering&lt;/strong&gt; for enhanced PWM resolution&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Capture/Compare&lt;/strong&gt; for position sensing and multi-axis synchronization&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The TCC peripheral is optimized for &lt;strong&gt;motor control&lt;/strong&gt;, offering features not available in basic Timer/Counter (TC) modules.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
